ladders.explanation:
Integer division and remainder operations are the fundamental arithmetic operations that enable factorization. The intuition is that we can determine if one integer divides another by checking if the remainder is zero. Specifically, for integers a and b (b ≠ 0), a % b gives the remainder when a is divided by b. If a % b == 0, then b divides a evenly, meaning b is a factor of a. Integer division a // b gives the quotient, which is what remains after dividing out factor b. These two operations work together: we use modulo to check for divisibility, then use integer division to reduce the number after extracting a factor. Time complexity for each division/modulo operation is O(1) for fixed-size integers. Space complexity is O(1). This building block connects to the basic operation of checking if one number divides another. Common mistakes include: confusing / (float division) with // (integer division), not handling division by zero, and misunderstanding negative numbers (though factorization typically deals with positive integers). The real code pattern uses % for checking divisibility and // for updating n after factor extraction.

Pseudocode:
function check_divisibility(a, b):
    return a % b == 0

function divide_out_factor(a, b):
    return a // b

Checking divisibility is the most fundamental operation in factorization algorithms. The intuition is simple: if a can be divided by b without leaving a remainder, then b is a factor of a. Mathematically, a is divisible by b if there exists an integer k such that a = b × k. In programming, we check this using the modulo operator: a % b == 0. The modulo operator returns the remainder when a is divided by b. If the remainder is zero, then b divides a evenly. This operation has O(1) time complexity for fixed-size integers. Space complexity is O(1). This basic operation feeds into the building block of integer division and remainder operations. Common mistakes include: not handling the case where b = 0 (division by zero is undefined), confusing divisibility with factors (all divisors are factors, but not all factors are prime), and not considering that 1 divides every integer. The real code pattern is a simple boolean check using the modulo operator.

Pseudocode:
function is_divisible(a, b):
    if b == 0:
        return False  # or raise error
    return a % b == 0
